So what do you want to do? 

1. Pass the exception on to your caller?  In which case get rid of the try-catch

2. Signal a different exception on to the caller - maybe one with a more appropriate error message for the specific circumstances?  Then make and throw a new exception object with a better error message.

3. Do something to handle the situation - at the very least, maybe display an error message?  Log the event to enable debugging? Then write code in the catch-block to do that. And then you have to decide what happens next.

Fundamentally, this is a design issue. IO errors happen. So how does this method that you&#39;re writing want to handle IO errors?

